Evidently, most devolved units have since made some strides. Also, there is consensus that not all devolved functions received commensurate funding. Regardless, there are legion reasons to believe that our devolved units have not demonstrated prudent utilisation of resources allocated, much less, provided efficient public service proportionate to the resources availed. Two reasons inform this unfortunate reality.
First, most county governments were founded on weak systems of resource management. Instructively, they woke up to colossal monies which they couldn’t immediately figure out what they were meant for. In reaction, officers went to fetch harvesting baskets. The looting that took place in the first 5 years of devolution is incomparable.



